	)
	(text "* I/O pull-ups\n"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 80.01 163.83 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "a37e45cf-436a-4189-b8a2-d69f3607f7e3")
	)
	(text "* Two main LOGICAL buses are routed throughout the board:\n\n  - USER: The USER bus is focused on controlling the board itself (SoC/MCU), e.g. setting up\n    configuration, issuing commands, retrieving collected data, etc. It has a single physical\n    bus with at most two wires. It can be a multi-master bus, when configured as I2C. Also,\n    as a rule, in this bus, the board (SoC/MCU) acts as a SLAVE, but depending on the mode of\n    operation, the bus can be used as a secondary PHER bus.\n\n  - PHER: The Pheripheral bus is where the devices the board controls directly are located;\n    e.g. the fuel gauge, battery charger, miscellaneous devices like screens or EEPROMs, etc.\n    For this bus, the board (SoC/MCU) acts strictly as a MASTER. It is separated in two physical\n    buses.\n\n* The board operates in two distinct and fixed modes, programmable at the firmware level:\n\n  - STANDALONE: The board is meant to run without supervision. It will be configured by default\n    in SoC/MCU firmware, or if enabled, interactively via a pre-specified \"HAT\" (if supported;\n    e.g. additional EEPROM storage, screen with touch or buttons, etc.). In this mode, the board\n    acts as MASTER in both USER and PHER buses.\n\n  - MANAGED: The board is meant to be controlled by a host system. The board acts as a MASTER\n    in the PHER bus, and as a SLAVE in the USER bus.\n\n* The physical buses for PHER and USER support specific bus types, selectable at firmware level:\n\n  - USER1: I2C1, LPUART2 or USART1.\n  - PHER1: I2C2.\n  - PHER2: I2C3, SPI1, I2S1 or COMP2.\n\n  See Pinouts on the table below.\n\n* For USER1 and PHER1, Pull-ups are always present, and pull to VCC, which can be either 3.3V\n  or 5V depending on physical board configuration. To the SoC/MCU all lines are 5V-tolerant\n  except for pins PA4 and PA5. However, try to avoid presenting 5V on any non-5V bus.\n\n* 4 initially unallocated GPIOs are available: GP1_IRQ2, GP2, GP3 and GP4. They'll generally\n  be used for the PHER buses. GP1_IRQ2 doubles as an interrupt line for peripherals when\n  necessary (e.g. touchscreens, sensors, etc.). All GPIOs can act as ADC lines. GP3 and GP4\n  can additionally be set up as DACs.\n\n* Of all GPIOs, only PA4 and PA5 (GP3 and GP4, respectively) are NOT 5V-tolerant. When setting\n  any pin to be an ADC, max voltage is 3.6V."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 163.83 48.26 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1 1)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "cece659e-3ec9-4ee7-bd6c-498bfbdb264f")
	)
